            <fr:addr type="user">hoas-pros</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hoas-pros.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Pros of HOAS">Pros of HOAS</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Discussion</fr:taxon>
            <fr:authors />
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The most major advantage of HOAS is that it frees the language implementor from having to think hard about substitution. In <fr:link type="local" href="named-variables.xml" addr="named-variables" title="Named Variables">approaches with named variables</fr:link> the user must handle capture-avoidance, generation of fresh names, and equality checking of variables. <fr:link type="local" href="debruijn.xml" addr="debruijn" title="DeBruijn Indices">DeBruijn indices</fr:link> are much easier to manage, but the user must still handle shifting variables up and down. With HOAS, substitution is as simple as possible. For instance, an evaluator for the <fr:link type="local" href="hoas.xml" addr="hoas" title="Higher-Order Abstract Syntax">lambda calculus defined with HOAS</fr:link> looks like the following.
  <fr:pre>eval :: Term -&gt; Term
eval (Lam e) = Lam e
eval (App f v) =
  case eval f of
    Lam e -&gt; e (eval v)
    _ -&gt; undefined</fr:pre>
  Here, <fr:code>e (eval v)</fr:code> is the act of substitution. Substitution is so simple that we don't even need to define it as a separate procedure -- it's quite literally as easy as calling a function.</fr:p>
